<subSubSection id="7BFFEAD3FFFFA70A0CB0FF6BFB9AA748" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="335AB958FFFFA70A0CB0FF6BFB9AA748" blockId="48.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0CB0FF6BFEFDA691" bold="true" box="[199,332,229,255]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species name refers to the long marginal scales of male sternite 5 (Lat. 
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0888FF6BFAFCA690" box="[1279,1357,229,254]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">longus</emphasis>
: long; 
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0CE0FE82FF4DA74B" box="[151,252,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">limbatus</emphasis>
: bordered) and alludes to the close relationship with 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFFFA70A0F1DFE82FB92A74B" authorityName="Duda" authorityYear="1925" box="[874,1059,268,293]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequilimbata">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0F1DFE82FB92A74B" box="[874,1059,268,293]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">L. aequilimbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7BFFEAD3FFFFA70A0CB0FEBCFB7EA7F4" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="335AB958FFFFA70A0CB0FEBCFB7EA7F4" blockId="48.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0CB0FEBCFED1A722" bold="true" box="[199,352,306,332]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Distribution</emphasis>
. At present only known from the 
<typeStatus id="EC5E07FAFFFFA70A0E9AFEBCFCAEA722" box="[749,799,306,332]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">type</typeStatus>
locality in central 
<collectingCountry id="4BF2F9C8FFFFA70A0F8DFEBCFB8BA722" box="[1018,1082,306,332]" name="Chile" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Chile</collectingCountry>
where it occurs at moderately high elevations (
<quantity id="F41D14BDFFFFA70A0D2DFED7FDA0A71D" box="[346,529,345,371]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.45" metricValueMax="2.6" metricValueMin="2.3" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" unit="m" value="2450.0" valueMax="2600.0" valueMin="2300.0">
<geoCoordinate id="56D1DF9FFFFFA70A0D2DFED7FE2CA71D" box="[346,413,345,371]" degrees="2,300" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" precision="55" value="2.3">2,300</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate id="56D1DF9FFFFFA70A0DEBFED7FE5FA71D" box="[412,494,345,371]" degrees="2,600" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" precision="55" value="-2.6">–2,600</geoCoordinate>
m
</quantity>
). The widespread Chilean species 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFFFA70A0FDEFED7FBC6A71C" authorityName="Richards" authorityYear="1931" box="[937,1143,345,370]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="neocurvinervis">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0FDEFED7FBC6A71C" box="[937,1143,345,370]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">L. neocurvinervis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from the same locality (see Material examined) but occurs at significantly lower elevations (
<quantity id="F41D14BDFFFFA70A0856FE0EFB73A7F4" box="[1057,1218,384,410]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="12.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" unit="m" value="900.0" valueMax="1200.0" valueMin="600.0">600–1,200 m</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7BFFEAD3FFFFA70A0CB0FE28FE79A4C6" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="335AB958FFFFA70A0CB0FE28FE79A4C6" blockId="48.[151,1436,151,680]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0CB0FE28FEFAA7AE" bold="true" box="[199,331,422,448]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Discussion</emphasis>
. This species is very close to 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFFFA70A0EC5FE29FCDDA7AE" authorityName="Duda" authorityYear="1925" box="[690,876,423,448]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequilimbata">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0EC5FE29FCDDA7AE" box="[690,876,423,448]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">L. aequilimbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. As discussed under the latter, 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFFFA70A0896FE29FA2AA7AE" authorityName="Duda" authorityYear="1925" box="[1249,1435,423,448]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequilimbata">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0896FE29FA2AA7AE" box="[1249,1435,423,448]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">L. aequilimbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows considerable variation in the length of marginal scales of male sternite 5, one of the characters that separate the two species. We are nonetheless confident that 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFFFA70A0F3CFE7AFC4EA463" authorityName="Buck &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2009" box="[843,1023,500,525]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longilimbata">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0F3CFE7AFC4EA463" box="[843,1023,500,525]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">L. longilimbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in fact a good species because of additional surstylar differences (see Description) and because a male of 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFFFA70A0F93FD94FB2FA45D" authorityName="Duda" authorityYear="1925" box="[996,1182,538,563]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequilimbata">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0F93FD94FB2FA45D" box="[996,1182,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">L. aequilimbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion id="F12177BAFFFFA70A0892FD94FA26A45A" box="[1253,1431,538,564]" country="Argentina" name="Jujuy" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Jujuy Province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="4BF2F9C8FFFFA70A0CE0FDCFFEBDA435" box="[151,268,577,603]" name="Argentina" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(the locality closest to the 
<typeStatus id="EC5E07FAFFFFA70A0E15FDCFFD24A435" box="[610,661,577,603]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">type</typeStatus>
locality of 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFFFA70A0F5FFDCFFC50A434" authority="Buck &amp; Marshall, 2009" authorityName="Buck &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2009" box="[808,993,577,602]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longilimbata" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0F5FFDCFFC50A434" box="[808,993,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">L. longilimbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="1AA2D831FFFFA70A0F9BFDCFFB95A435" box="[1004,1060,577,603]" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
) has relatively short scales on sternite 5 (in 
<taxonomicName id="F4E5C2DBFFFFA70A0D4BFDE6FE48A4EF" authorityName="Duda" authorityYear="1925" box="[316,505,616,641]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="48" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequilimbata">
<emphasis id="0191654AFFFFA70A0D4BFDE6FE48A4EF" box="[316,505,616,641]" italics="true" pageId="48" pageNumber="49">L. aequilimbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the longest scales were found in specimens from Lake Titicaca, towards the northern end of its range).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
